  "description": [
    "12 True to Type WHO WILL ENCAGE POETS TO WRITE FOR HOOVER By GILBERT SELDES Sometimes in obscure streets you find little hand printed signs which aspire to verse They begin with No Trust No Bust which in my seventh year I be lieved the perfection of wit and go on to longer and more sustained flights For the best delicatessen and good cold meats buy your groceries at H L Schmidt Years ago rhymes were considered good advertising there were the entertaining pictures and jingles of Spot less Town and several other series but today adver tisers stfck to grim prose for the most part and to purple patches of fine writing for the rest And this is not the only field from which poetry has been driven A hundred years ago a radical journal like the New Masses would have had dozens of satires or invectives in verse Today as the authors of the Provincetown remind us in Bobby Edwards lines they draw fat women for the masses denuded big ungainly lasses How does that help the working classes The art of the engraver has taken the place of the art of the poet No Political Satire Even"
  ],
